post_text:
Kids Oasis summer program is planning a tentative opening of July 6th and will end on August 6th.
Times will be from 8:00 am to 11:30 am Monday-Thursday.
Held at KIDS OASIS - 601 West 9th.

Because of space restrictions this summer, children who will be in 1st grade in the fall through 6th grade will be able to attend (not pre-K as we have in the past). Spaces will be reserved on a first come, first serve basis. In order for your child(ren) to attend, a waiver must be signed and returned ASAP. Please contact Carlene Larington at carlenelarington@opsd.org to receive a form to fill out and the waiver. If not returned by June 19 - the slot will not be available. Please do not send your child(ren) without receiving a confirmation email or phone call.

http://www.opsd.org/docs/district/BannerImages/KidsOasis.jpg

Plans are in place to begin online learning for Prairie View School students on Monday, March 30. Parents and guardians can come to the school anytime between 7:00 a.m. and 7:00 p.m. on Monday, March 23, to:
1) drop-off school library books and text books, and
2) pick-up personal belongings of students, third quarter report cards, and other important items (including Chromebooks) needed for online learning.

See the details below.

post_text: Hi! My name is Brandi Lippert and I am new to Ogallala. In the past I worked with others at Christmas time the "Adopt a Grandparent” initiative in our communities. I would like to continue this initiative in Ogallala. Adopt a Grandparent initiative provides a pair of socks and lotion wrapped to each resident in the nursing home (Indian Hills). We have a total of 37 residents. I am also the Ogallala Middle School Counselor where I plan to have some students make cards and deliver the socks and lotion to the residents on December 17, 2019. You can adopt one senior for $12 or 3 for $30. If you would like to adopt a grandparent feel free to drop money off at the Middle School or mail them. Please make checks payable to Ogallala Public School District with memo of "adopt a senior." If you want to participate please let me know so I can document and make sure we have enough socks and lotion for all residents.

post_text:
Sources of Strength is a suicide prevention program that uses a color wheel for Creating Sources of Strength that include positive friends, mental health, family support, mentors, healthy activities, and generosity. The overall goal of Sources of Strength is to support students who have sadness, anxiety, or depression within the school and community. The main goal is to spread hope, health, and strength by focusing on stories of hope rather than trauma.

November we are celebrating Generosity/Thankfulness. Sources of Strength identifies Generosity as one of the 8 strengths needed for living a healthy life. Each week we are promoting a family challenge and encouraging you to share a photo on your favorite social media site completing the challenge. This month place something that you are thankful for and hashtag #thankfulnesschallenge and #sourcesofstrength. Feel free to post any pictures of anything that you do at home do promote thankfulness!

post_text: For Veteran's Day yesterday (November 11, 2019) Prairie view 6th Grade students were honored by a visit from four military veterans. Left to right: Wes Schmer (served in the Navy during the Iran Crisis), Gary Bush (served in the Navy in the Vietnam War), Jim Kampschneider (served in the Army in Germany during the Vietnam War), and Darrel Munson (served in the Marines in the Vietnam War). Thank you to all who have served, or are currently serving, our Country!

post_text: Every Friday, Mrs. Byrn and Mrs. Skalsky’s Physical Education Classes participate in Fitness Friday. Students rotate through 8 different fitness stations; which they perform for 1 minute. Between each station, Students run 2 laps around the gym. Fitness Friday is designed for Student’s to build their cardiorespiratory endurance, muscular strength, muscular endurance, flexibility, and overall fitness level.

post_text:
7th Annual Indian Marching Festival

Several Nebraska area bands are invited each year to compete in the Street Marching and Field Marching routines in Ogallala. The parade is free to the public so please show up and support the participating students!

The Street Marching begins at 1:00pm with the best viewing along Spruce Street. The Judges Station is near 4th and Spruce while the end of the route is at the High School Football Field.

The Field Marching begins at 2:30pm at the Football Field following the Street Marching event. There is an entry fee of $3 for the Field Marching event and Activity Passes cannot be used. The entry fee helps fund the Music Boosters and supports the students of the Fine Arts Department. Awards for both events will follow the Field Marching event.

There will be concessions at the Football Field with the proceeds to help support the Music Boosters.

If you need any other details please feel free to contact any of the Booster Club members, including Lance Larington at Nebraska Printworks, or Mike Schlake at Ogallala Public Schools.
